</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>It was: I told you that before:&mdash;what intere&s;ts you &s;o deeply for Sir Harry Har|low?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>What intere&s;ts me! what!&mdash;O Charles&mdash;forbear to que&s;tion me&mdash;it &s;tabs my heart:&mdash;I do be&s;eech you leave me to my&s;elf:&mdash;it turns my brain. Give me a minute's recol|lection.</P>
<STAGE>[Walks a&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now by my &s;oul, 'tis very &s;trange: it &s;taggers me. Su&s;picions force upon me: no|thing is more evident than her di&s;order: it &s;mote her like a &s;troke of death&mdash;nay, 'tis mo&s;t palpable: her eyes are &s;taring wild with horror. Ah! 'tis &s;o; &s;he loves him. Cur&s;e upon him! he has prevail'd with her too.&mdash;Heavens! what a character is overthrown!</P>
<STAGE>[A&s;ide.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lady D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Charles, Charles, you mu&s;t be pa|tient in this bu&s;ine&s;s. Do not tru&s;t your infor|mation too implicitly; nor hurry on an expla|nation that you may repent of.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Dav.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mu&s;t I be patient, Madam? mu&s;t I permit the dire&s;t villain to &s;urvive?&mdash;and do you plead for him?&mdash;no, if my honour was not pledg'd to Dormer not to take up this affair without him, by my &s;oul a moment &s;hou'd not pa&s;s before my &s;word &s;hou'd make its pa&s;&s;age to the traitor's heart!</P>
</SP>
<PB N="63" REF="66">
<SP>
