<SP>
<SPEAKER>Lord D.</SPEAKER>
<P>Do&s;t think me &s;o far &s;unk in honour, as to &s;hrink from this di&s;cu&s;&s;ion? Dormer's en|titled to an honourable &s;atisfaction, and I &s;hall give it him immediately. Before we part how|ever, Lady Davenant, let me own that I am penetrated with remor&s;e for my conduct to you. Tho' I a&s;k nothing for my&s;elf, I am not out of hope that you will ca&s;t an eye of pity and pro|tection on that guiltle&s;s &s;ufferer, who, if I fall, will be the partner of your widowhood:&mdash;&s;he is young and beautiful; and, if your influence over Dormer is exerted in her favour, &s;he may
